<dl id="sa0512an"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="sa" href="#sa0512an">SA (VI.A) </a>: <a href="../../ff/fnbs/ssaall.htm#sa0512an"> 512(an)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> a drink is shorter than a story / (pass the bottle): <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="sa0512an"><li>FW 95.27 </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#sa0512an">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#sa0512an">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#sa0512an">MS BL 47472-282</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:106 <a name="dd5" href="../../ff/fdra/dda.htm#dd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/dd5.htm#sa0512an">Draft: I.4&sect;1.5</a>/2.5</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">&lsquo;<mark>A drink is shorter than a story</mark>.&rsquo; &hellip; Kelly (Manx Dict.) says that the Manx version is used &ldquo;when a person is desired to cease in his story and to pass the bottle.&rdquo; <small> Thomas F. O'Rahilly, <a name="TFOR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#TFOR"><cite title="source">A Miscellany of Irish Proverbs</cite></a> (Dublin: Talbot Press, 1922) 118-9, &para;357</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Not in 1939 edition. </mm> </dd></dl>
